Maoist Third-Worldist Mario 5/26/2025 11:54 PM
Finished reading the 1957-1959 run of The Eternaut. An Argentine graphic novel that recently got a Netflix show adaptation. It was an incredibly good read in regards of plot; the artstyle clearly shows its age, yet still remains pretty legible and engaging; greatly recommend it to anyone that may like sci-fi or apocalypse/post-apocalypse stories. Funnily enough, if there's anyone I would beg to read this, it would be Half-Life fans, especially those interested in the idea of the Seven Hour War, you'll find a lot of coincidences among the plotlines if you look at it through that lens, I won't spoil much of the details, but the idea that humanity is put against some incredibly overpowered external force and it is obligated to find how to resist and survive against all odds, alongside some interdimensional shenanigans; is sure to make for some excellent parallels with the game's universe. Next up I'll probably be reading the 1969 remake of the comic, which is far more politically charged due to the circumstances that Argentina was going through at that moment. (edited)

Maoist Third-Worldist Mario
Finished reading the 1957-1959 run of The Eternaut. An Argentine graphic novel that recently got a Netflix show adaptation. It was an incredibly good read in regards of plot; the artstyle clearly shows its age, yet still remains pretty legible and engaging; greatly recommend it to anyone that may like sci-fi or apocalypse/post-apocalypse stories. Funnily enough, if there's anyone I would beg to read this, it would be Half-Life fans, especially those interested in the idea of the Seven Hour War, you'll find a lot of coincidences among the plotlines if you look at it through that lens, I won't spoil much of the details, but the idea that humanity is put against some incredibly overpowered external force and it is obligated to find how to resist and survive against all odds, alongside some interdimensional shenanigans; is sure to make for some excellent parallels with the game's universe. Next up I'll probably be reading the 1969 remake of the comic, which is far more politically charged due to the circumstances that Argentina was going through at that moment. (edited)
Maoist Third-Worldist Mario 5/27/2025 7:41 PM
...Well that was quick. Finished the 1969 reboot of The Eternaut. A reboot and, unfortunately, a massive abridging of the original Argentine graphic novel. The production of this run was prematurely ended due to the political and artistic directions that Héctor Germán Oesterheld and Alberto Breccia, writer and artist respectively, were taking with the story, which clashed with the publisher. The plot, in its broad strokes, is pretty much the same as the original story, but the tone and intentions behind it are very different; Oesterheld was going for a far more accessible approach in the original run, almost just catering to teenagers who might not be interested in reading regular novels, but would love reading comics; this remake on the other hand is pretty much agitprop, and with reason, H.G.O. had his political ideals radicalized following the 1966 coup d'etat and subsequent military dictatorship that Argentina was going through and of which he was in staunch opposition to. The story has changed from the last bastions of humanity uniting to rebel against an incredible threat, to the world powers agreeing to give away a piece of land to a foreign invader and leaving the native inhabitants to fend for themselves. -# Gee, where have I heard that before? Anyways, if you liked the original run of The Eternaut, this is a good read too, especially if you want to understand the tonal shift seen in the 1972 The Eternaut, Second Part (a continuation of the '57 run), if you haven't read the original Eternaut and want to check this one out, please read the original first, it helps fill a lot of the blanks that this comic's rushed production had to make. (edited)

Maoist Third-Worldist Mario 7/28/2025 8:06 PM
After spending a good chunk of my afternoon reading someone's alt history worldbuilding, I was reminded of the short story Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius by Jorge Luis Borges; so I've decided to make a little write up recommending it. Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius is a story about a man discovering the encyclopedia of a different, seemingly parallel world, a world of complete idealism, that is expressed in everything from its philosophy, its history and its languages. All these things are handled and worded in such a fascinating way that can lead to some, pardon my language, mindfucks while you try wrapping your head around them; I won't delve much into the details, but it is this exploration of the impact of philosophy and languages in our lives that makes, at least in my opinion, this story so fascinating. Here I'll link both an English version (As a PDF of a book scan) and the original Spanish version (As text on a website, please use adblock.) of the story, it's about roughly 16 pages long; but I warn you: It's not an easy read. Borges is an author that employs an impressive amount of cross-references to authors from all around the world, events from any moment in human history, or even mundane places of his native Argentina constantly throughout his work, so don't be afraid to keep some extra tabs open for context if you ever feel lost while reading. But please, do read it, you won't regret it, Borges is my favorite argentine author of all time and it is because of stories like this one. (edited)
